<DOC><DOCNO> AP881205-0065 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0814EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Defection     12-05 0202</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Japan-Defection,0213</SECOND><HEAD>East German Musician Defects In Tokyo</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An East German musician in Japan with a Berlinorchestra has defected after seeking asylum at the West GermanEmbassy in Tokyo, a Foreign Ministry official said today.   Gerhard Gobel, 43, a violist with the Berlin Radio SymphonyOrchestra, arrived in West Germany today after leaving Japan on aLufthansa flight Sunday evening, said the Japanese official, whospoke on condition of anonymity.   ``Since Gobel is a musician, there are no special politicalmotives for the defection,'' the official said, without elaborating.   According to Kyodo News Service, Gobel did not show up for theorchestra's Saturday night performance in Kofu, 68 miles west ofTokyo.   Instead, he went to the West German Embassy in Tokyo and askedfor asylum. Embassy officials refused to comment.   His absence was noticed when the orchestra arrived in Hiroshima,429 miles southwest of Tokyo, on Saturday, Kyodo said.   The Berlin Radio Symphony Orchestra arrived in Japan on Nov. 30and is scheduled to perform in six Japanese cities before leavingDec. 19.   In November, four East Germans on tour with a chorus from Dresdenalso were granted asylum at the West German Embassy in Tokyo.</TEXT></DOC>